const title = "Built-In Grill Burner Won't Ignite | Lynx, Fire Magic, Twin Eagles | $120";
const description = "Single zone won't spark, all zones won't click, Lynx 9V battery, hot surface igniter, electrode replacement. ~30% resolve at $120 dx. Same-day SoCal.";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Why won't my Lynx Professional E-series grill spark on any zone?",
    a: "Nine times out of ten on Lynx Pro E-series and Sedona it's the 9V battery in the battery tray (OEM 80489). Most owners don't know the battery exists. $5 part, 5 minutes. We see this 6 to 10 times a month. The next most likely is the spark module ($180 to $280, 30-minute swap). Lynx L, M, N, P, and Q series use 110V hot surface ignition (no battery), so the failure path is different — usually the hot surface igniter element itself."
  },
  {
    q: "One burner won't light but the others work fine. What is it?",
    a: "Single-zone failure points to electrode (ceramic igniter) or burner cap level. Most common: spark electrode cracked or fouled by grease and spider webs. $200 to $340 per zone replacement. Second most common: burner cap misaligned after the customer cleaned the grill. We re-seat it at the diagnostic, no parts. We see this last one 25 to 30% of single-zone calls; we tell you straight at $120 dx instead of selling you parts."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between Lynx Pro E and L-series ignition?",
    a: "Pro E-series and Sedona use battery-powered piezo or spark-module ignition with a 9V battery in a tray under the control panel. L, M, N, P, and Q series moved to 110V hot surface ignition. Hot surface uses a glow element (similar to gas oven igniters) and runs off the grill's 120V supply. No battery. When the L-series doesn't ignite, we test the igniter element resistance and the 120V supply, not a battery."
  },
  {
    q: "How much does spark module replacement cost?",
    a: "Mid-tier (Coyote, Blaze, Bull, Summerset, RCS) spark module: $180 to $340. Pro-tier (Lynx, Fire Magic, Twin Eagles, DCS, Hestan, Wolf outdoor): $440 to $680. Module sourcing is usually 3 to 7 days for pro-tier through authorized parts pipelines. We carry common modules in stock for Lynx and Fire Magic same-day in coastal branches."
  },
  {
    q: "Why does coastal salt air destroy grill electrodes faster?",
    a: "Salt deposits accumulate on the ceramic insulator and the steel electrode tip, accelerating corrosion 2 to 3 times the inland rate. Malibu, Newport Beach, Pacific Palisades, Manhattan Beach, and Laguna installations see electrode failure at year 4 to 6 vs year 8 to 12 inland. We stock extra electrodes in our West Hollywood, Thousand Oaks, and Irvine branches specifically for coastal patterns."
  },
  {
    q: "What's your warranty?",
    a: "90 days SDAR labor warranty on every repair. BHGS #A49573 and EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410). BBB A+ accredited."
  }
];

